Task 3: Scale up

Why each element is added

- Extra server (4th server total) — splitting the stack into dedicated tiers requires one
  server per component. Previously, the web server, application server, and database
  all shared the same machine; now each lives on its own host and can be scaled,
  secured, and maintained independently.

- HAProxy configured as a cluster (2 load balancers) — the single load balancer
  was a SPOF. Adding a second HAProxy node in an Active-Active cluster means both
  nodes handle live traffic simultaneously. They share a virtual IP and exchange
  heartbeat signals — if one node fails, the other keeps serving requests with zero
  downtime.

- Dedicated web server (Nginx) — Nginx is optimised for serving static assets
  (HTML, CSS, images, JS) and terminating TLS. Isolating it allows tuning of worker
  processes, connection limits, and caching without affecting the application layer.

- Dedicated application server — the app server runs business logic (Python, PHP,
  Node.js, etc.) and is often the most CPU- and memory-intensive component. A
  dedicated machine allows horizontal scaling (adding more app servers behind the
  LB) without touching the web or DB tiers.

- Dedicated database server — databases are I/O-bound and need predictable disk
  and memory resources. Isolating the DB prevents resource contention with the app
  layer, allows stricter firewall rules (only the app server can reach port 3306), and
  enables DB-optimised storage configuration (fast SSDs, large RAM for the buffer
  pool)
